    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix out-of-bounds array access in get_sin_cos function\n\n### Summary\nThe `get_sin_cos` function in the PHY tools module can access memory outside the bounds of its lookup table when processing negative phase values. This occurs because the index calculation for negative phases doesn't properly handle the boundary condition where the result equals the table size.\n\nSpecifically, when `phase` is a negative integer (e.g., -1.0, -2.0), the function computes an index of exactly `4 * LUT_SIN_RESOL`, which exceeds the valid range. This leads to undefined behavior and potential crashes.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Call `get_sin_cos(-1.0)` \n2. Observe that the computed index equals 512\n3. Note that valid indices should be in range [0, 511]\n4. The function attempts to access `LUTSin[512]` which is beyond the array bounds\n\nThis issue manifests as incorrect SINR calculations during channel estimation when the phase offset happens to be a negative integer value.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/get_sin_cos.c`: Added bounds checking after index calculation to prevent out-of-bounds access\n"
}